<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-956-284  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 956 284.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 16 1989 v23 n2 p108(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Unraveling SQL for MIS pros: trainers should be versed in thelanguage's many far-reaching effects. (Structured Query Language)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sayles, Jonathan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>SQL, the basis of many current relational database managementsystems, adds some new wrinkles to the MIS training process.andP;  Thelanguage is new to many mainframe shops, as IBM's DB2 is arelatively recent addition.andP;  Its purpose is not yet well definedin the production work of the department.andP;  The language takesdifferent forms in the various relational DBMS products now inuse.andP;  To face these issues, MIS managers and trainers must beprepared to answer some specific questions about the language.andO;The training process should take into consideration to what endsSQL will be used and who will be using it.andP;  Trainers need only asurface knowledge about the various resources used in the DBMSdevelopment process.andP;  MIS managers must be prepared to beretrained in new procedures, or face an ineffective product.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISTraining of EmployeesStructured Query LanguageStrategic PlanningUser NeedsComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>